<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <title>Twitch Bible Bot</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <main class="container">
    <section class="hero card">
      <h1>Twitch Bible Bot</h1>
      <p>Public Twitch bot for Bible verses. Streamers can connect their Twitch account, enable the bot for their channel, and choose a default translation.</p>
      <div class="actions">
        <% if (user) { %>
          <a class="button" href="/dashboard">Open dashboard</a>
        <% } else { %>
          <a class="button" href="/auth/twitch">Connect with Twitch</a>
        <% } %>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="grid">
      <article class="card">
        <h2>How it works</h2>
        <p>After a streamer connects with Twitch, the bot stores their channel and joins it automatically. Viewers can then type references like <code>John 3:16</code> or <code>Psalms 23:1 WEB</code>.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h2>Translations</h2>
        <p>The bot uses the HelloAO Free Use Bible API and supports friendly aliases like <code>KJV</code>, <code>WEB</code>, <code>GLV</code>, and <code>NET</code> mapped to HelloAO translation IDs.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h2>Deploy</h2>
        <p>Host on Railway, set Twitch app variables, and keep one central bot account online for all connected channels.</p>
      </article>
    </section>
  </main>
</body>
</html>
